# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metabolomics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] In biochemistry, **metabolic flux** (often referred to as **flux**) is the rate of turnover of molecules through a metabolic pathway.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Flux is regulated by the enzymes involved in a pathway.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Within cells, regulation of flux is vital for all metabolic pathways to regulate the pathway's activity under different conditions.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Flux is therefore of great interest in metabolic network modelling, where it is analysed via flux balance analysis and metabolic control analysis.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] In this manner, flux is the movement of matter through metabolic networks that are connected by metabolites and cofactors, and is therefore a way of describing the activity of the metabolic network as a whole using a single characteristic.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] It is easiest to describe the flux of metabolites through a pathway by considering the reaction steps individually.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Furthermore, it is observed that throughout a steady-state pathway, the flux is determined to varying degrees by all steps in the pathway.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The degree of influence is measured by the flux control coefficient.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Cellular metabolism is represented by a large number of metabolic reactions involving the conversion of the carbon source (usually glucose) into the building blocks needed for macromolecular biosynthesis.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] These reactions form metabolic networks within cells.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] These networks can then be used to study metabolism within cells.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] To allow these networks to interact, a tight connection between them is necessary.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] This connection is provided by usage of common cofactors such as ATP, ADP, NADH and NADPH.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] In addition to this, sharing of some metabolites between the different networks further tightens the connections between the different networks.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Existing metabolic networks control the movement of molecules through their enzymatic steps by regulating enzymes that catalyze irreversible reactions.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The movement of molecules through reversible steps is generally unregulated by enzymes, but rather regulated by the concentration of products and reactants.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Irreversible reactions at regulated steps of a pathway have a negative free energy change, thereby promoting spontaneous reactions in one direction only.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Reversible reactions have no or very small free energy change.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] As a result, the movement of molecules through a metabolic network is governed by simple chemical equilibria (at reversible steps), with specific key enzymes that are subject to regulation (at irreversible steps).
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] A result that may seem at first counter intuitive, is that regulated steps tends to have small flux control coefficients.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The reason is that these steps are part of a control system that stabilizes fluxes, hence a perturbation in the activity of a regulated step will inevitably trigger the control system to resist the perturbation, hence the flux control coefficients will tend to be small.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] This explains why, for example, that phosphofructokinase in glycolysis has such as small flux control coefficient.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Metabolic fluxes are a function of gene expression, translation, post translational protein modifications and protein-metabolite interactions.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The function of the central carbon metabolism (metabolism of glucose) has been fine-tuned to exactly meet the needs of the building blocks and Gibbs free energy in conjunction with cell growth.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] There is therefore tight regulation of the fluxes through the central carbon metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Considering the above, the metabolic fluxes can be described as the ultimate representation of the cellular phenotype when expressed under certain conditions.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Research has shown that cells undergoing rapid growth have shown changes in their metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] These changes are observed with regards to glucose metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The changes in metabolism occur because the rate of metabolism controls various signal transduction pathways that coordinate the activation of transcription factors as well as determining cell-cycle progress.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Growing cells require synthesis of new nucleotides, membranes and protein components.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] These materials can be obtained from carbon metabolism (e.g. glucose metabolism) or from peripheral metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The enhanced flux observed in abnormally growing cells is brought about by high glucose uptake.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Metabolic flux and more specifically how metabolism is affected due to changes in the various pathways has grown in importance since it was observed that tumour cells exhibit enhanced glucose metabolism compared to normal cells.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Through studying these changes, it is possible to better understand the mechanisms of cell growth and where possible develop treatments to counter the effects of enhanced metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] There are several ways of measuring fluxes, however all of these are indirect.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] Due to this, these methods make one key assumption which is that all fluxes into a given intracellular metabolite pool balance all the fluxes out of the pool.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] This assumption means that for a given metabolic network the balances around each metabolite impose a number of constraints on the system.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The techniques currently used mainly revolve around the use of either nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) or gas chromatography–mass spectrometry (GC–MS).
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] In order to avoid the complexity of data analysis, a simpler method of estimating flux ratios has recently been developed which is based on cofeeding unlabelled and uniformly 13C labelled glucose.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] The metabolic intermediate patterns are then analysed using NMR spectroscopy.
[src:metabolomics/flux-metabolism] This method can also be used to determine the metabolic network topologies.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Lipidomics research involves the identification and quantification of the thousands of cellular lipid molecular species and their interactions with other lipids, proteins, and other metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Investigators in lipidomics examine the structures, functions, interactions, and dynamics of cellular lipids and the changes that occur during perturbation of the system.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Han and Gross first defined the field of lipidomics through integrating the specific chemical properties inherent in lipid molecular species with a comprehensive mass spectrometric approach.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Although lipidomics is under the umbrella of the more general field of "metabolomics", lipidomics is itself a distinct discipline due to the uniqueness and functional specificity of lipids relative to other metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] In lipidomic research, a vast amount of information quantitatively describing the spatial and temporal alterations in the content and composition of different lipid molecular species is accrued after perturbation of a cell through changes in its physiological or pathological state.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Information obtained from these studies facilitates mechanistic insights into changes in cellular function.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Therefore, lipidomic studies play an essential role in defining the biochemical mechanisms of lipid-related disease processes through identifying alterations in cellular lipid metabolism, trafficking and homeostasis.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The growing attention on lipid research is also seen from the initiatives underway of the LIPID Metabolites And Pathways Strategy (LIPID MAPS Consortium). and The European Lipidomics Initiative (ELIfe).
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Lipids are a diverse and ubiquitous group of compounds which have many key biological functions, such as acting as structural components of cell membranes, serving as energy storage sources and participating in signaling pathways.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Lipids may be broadly defined as hydrophobic or amphipathic small molecules that originate entirely or in part from two distinct types of biochemical subunits or "building blocks": ketoacyl and isoprene groups.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The huge structural diversity found in lipids arises from the biosynthesis of various combinations of these building blocks.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] For example, glycerophospholipids are composed of a glycerol backbone linked to one of approximately 10 possible headgroups and also to 2 fatty acyl/alkyl chains, which in turn may have 30 or more different molecular structures.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] In practice, not all possible permutations are detected experimentally, due to chain preferences depending on the cell type and also to detection limits - nevertheless several hundred distinct glycerophospholipid molecular species have been detected in mammalian cells.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Plant **chloroplast thylakoid** membranes however, have *unique lipid composition* as they are deficient in phospholipids.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Also, their largest constituent, *monogalactosyl diglyceride or MGDG*, does not form aqueous bilayers.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Nevertheless, dynamic studies reveal a normal lipid bilayer organisation in thylakoid membranes.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Most methods of lipid extraction and isolation from biological samples exploit the high solubility of hydrocarbon chains in organic solvents.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Given the diversity in lipid classes, it is not possible to accommodate all classes with a common extraction method.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The traditional Bligh/Dyer procedure uses chloroform/methanol-based protocols that include phase partitioning into the organic layer.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] However, several protocols now exist, with newer methods overcoming the shortcomings of older ones and solving problems associated with, for example, targeted lipid isolation or high throughput data collection .
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Most protocols work relatively well for a variety of physiologically relevant lipids but they have to be adapted for species with particular properties and low-abundance and labile lipid metabolites .
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The simplest method of lipid separation is the use of thin layer chromatography (TLC).
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Although not as sensitive as other methods of lipid detection, it offers a rapid and comprehensive screening tool prior to more sensitive and sophisticated techniques.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Solid-phase extraction (SPE) chromatography is useful for rapid, preparative separation of crude lipid mixtures into different lipid classes.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] This involves the use of prepacked columns containing silica or other stationary phases to separate glycerophospholipids, fatty acids, cholesteryl esters, glycerolipids, and sterols from crude lipid mixtures.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] High-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC or LC) is extensively used in lipidomic analysis to separate lipids prior to mass analysis.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Separation can be achieved by either normal-phase (NP) HPLC or reverse-phase (RP) HPLC.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] For example, NP-HPLC effectively separates glycerophospholipids on the basis of headgroup polarity, whereas RP-HPLC effectively separates fatty acids such as eicosanoids on the basis of chain length, degree of unsaturation and substitution.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] For global, untargeted lipidomic studies it is common to use both RP and NP or Hydrophilic Interaction Liquid Chromatrography (HILC) columns for increased lipidome coverage.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The application of nano-flow liquid chromatography (nLC) proved thereby to be most efficient to enhance both general measurement sensitivity and lipidome coverage for a global lipidomics approach.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Chromatographic (HPLC/UHPLC) separation of lipids may either be performed offline or online where the eluate is integrated with the ionization source of a mass spectrometer.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] "Soft" ionization does not cause extensive fragmentation, so that comprehensive detection of an entire range of lipids within a complex mixture can be correlated to experimental conditions or disease state.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] In addition, the technique of atmospheric pressure chemical ionization (APCI) has become increasingly popular for the analysis of nonpolar lipids.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] ESI-MS was initially developed by Fenn and colleagues for analysis of biomolecules.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] It depends on the formation of gaseous ions from polar, thermally labile and mostly non-volatile molecules and thus is completely suitable for a variety of lipids.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] It is a soft-ionization method that rarely disrupts the chemical nature of the analyte prior to mass analysis.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Various ESI-MS methods have been developed for analysis of different classes, subclasses, and individual lipid species from biological extracts.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Comprehensive reviews of the methods and their application have recently been published.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The major advantages of ESI-MS are high accuracy, sensitivity, reproducibility, and the applicability of the technique to complex solutions without prior derivatization.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Han and coworkers have developed a method known as"shotgun lipidomics" which involves direct infusion of a crude lipid extract into an ESI source optimized for intrasource separation of lipids based on their intrinsic electrical properties.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] DESI mass spectrometry is an ambient ionization technique developed by Professor Zoltan Takáts, et al., in Professor Graham Cooks' group from Purdue University.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] It combines the ESI and desorption ionization techniques, by directing an electrically charged mist to the sample surface that is a few millimeters away.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The technique has been successfully applied to lipidomics as imaging tool to map the lipid distributions within tissue specimens.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] One of the advantages of DESI MS is that no matrix is required for tissue preparation, allowing multiple consecutive measurements on the same tissue specimen.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] DESI MS can also be used for imaging of lipids from tissue sections.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] MALDI mass spectrometry is a laser-based soft-ionization method often used for analysis of large proteins, but has been used successfully for lipids.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The lipid is mixed with a matrix, such as 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid, and applied to a sample holder as a small spot.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] A laser is fired at the spot, and the matrix absorbs the energy, which is then transferred to the analyte, resulting in ionization of the molecule.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] MALDI-Time-of-flight (MALDI-TOF) MS has become a very promising approach for lipidomics studies, particularly for the imaging of lipids from tissue slides.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The source for APCI is similar to ESI except that ions are formed by the interaction of the heated analyte solvent with a corona discharge needle set at a high electrical potential.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Primary ions are formed immediately surrounding the needle, and these interact with the solvent to form secondary ions that ultimately ionize the sample.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] APCI is particularly useful for the analysis of nonpolar lipids such as triacylglycerols, sterols, and fatty acid esters.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The high sensitivity of DESI in the lipid range makes it a powerful technique for the detection and mapping of lipids abundances within tissue specimens.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Recent developments in MALDI methods have enabled direct detection of lipids in-situ.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Abundant lipid-related ions are produced from the direct analysis of thin tissue slices when sequential spectra are acquired across a tissue surface that has been coated with a MALDI matrix.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Collisional activation of the molecular ions can be used to determine the lipid family and often structurally define the molecular species.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] These techniques enable detection of phospholipids, sphingolipids and glycerolipids in tissues such as heart, kidney and brain.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Furthermore, distribution of many different lipid molecular species often define anatomical regions within these tissues.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Lipid profiling is a targeted metabolomics platform that provides a comprehensive analysis of lipid species within a cell or tissue.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Profiling based on electrospray ionization tandem mass spectrometry (ESI-MS/MS) is capable of providing quantitative data and is adaptable to high throughput analyses.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The powerful approach of transgenics, namely deletion and/or overexpression of a gene product coupled with lipidomics, can give valuable insights into the role of biochemical pathways.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Lipid profiling techniques have also been applied to plants and microorganisms such as yeast.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] A combination of quantitative lipidomic data in conjunction with the corresponding transcriptional data (using gene-array methods) and proteomic data (using tandem MS) enables a systems biology approach to a more in-depth understanding of the metabolic or signaling pathways of interest.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] A major challenge for lipidomics, in particular for MS-based approaches, lies in the computational and bioinformatic demands of handling the large amount of data that arise at various stages along the chain of information acquisition and processing.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Chromatographic and MS data collection requires substantial efforts in spectral alignment and statistical evaluation of fluctuations in signal intensities.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Such variations have a multitude of origins, including biological variations, sample handling and analytical accuracy.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] As a consequence several replicates are normally required for reliable determination of lipid levels in complex mixtures.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Within the last few years, a number of software packages have been developed by various companies and research groups to analyze data generated by MS profiling of metabolites, including lipids.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The data processing for differential profiling usually proceed through several stages, including input file manipulation, spectral filtering, peak detection, chromatographic alignment, normalization, visualization, and data export.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] An example of metabolic profiling software is the freely-available Java-based Mzmine application.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Another is Metabolon, Inc's commercial applications for metabolomic analysis using proprietary software.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Recently MS-DIAL 4 software was integrated with a comprehensive lipidome atlas with retention time, collision cross-section and tandem mass spectrometry information for 117 lipid subclasses and 8,051 lipids.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Another objective of the information technology side of lipidomics involves the construction of metabolic maps from data on lipid structures and lipid-related protein and genes.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Some of these lipid pathways are extremely complex, for example the mammalian glycosphingolipid pathway.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] The establishment of searchable and interactive databases of lipids and lipid-related genes/proteins is also an extremely important resource as a reference for the lipidomics community.
[src:metabolomics/lipidomics] Integration of these databases with MS and other experimental data, as well as with metabolic networks offers an opportunity to devise therapeutic strategies to prevent or reverse these pathological states involving dysfunction of lipid-related processes.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] A **metabolic network** is the complete set of metabolic and physical processes that determine the physiological and biochemical properties of a cell.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] As such, these networks comprise the chemical reactions of metabolism, the metabolic pathways, as well as the regulatory interactions that guide these reactions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] With the sequencing of complete genomes, it is now possible to reconstruct the network of biochemical reactions in many organisms, from bacteria to human.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] Several of these networks are available online: Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG), EcoCyc, BioCyc and metaTIGER.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] Metabolic networks are powerful tools for studying and modelling metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] Metabolic networks can be used to detect comorbidity patterns in diseased patients.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] Certain diseases, such as obesity and diabetes, can be present in the same individual concurrently, sometimes one disease being a significant risk factor for the other disease.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] The disease phenotypes themselves are normally the consequence of the cell's inability to breakdown or produce an essential substrate.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] However, an enzyme defect at one reaction may affect the fluxes of other subsequent reactions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] These cascading effects couple the metabolic diseases associated with subsequent reactions resulting in comorbidity effects.
[src:metabolomics/metabolic-network] Thus, metabolic disease networks can be used to determine if two disorders are connected due to their correlated reactions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] In biochemistry, a **metabolite** is an intermediate or end product of metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] The term is usually used for small molecules.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] Metabolites have various functions, including fuel, structure, signaling, stimulatory and inhibitory effects on enzymes, catalytic activity of their own (usually as a cofactor to an enzyme), defense, and interactions with other organisms (e.g. pigments, odorants, and pheromones).
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] A primary metabolite is directly involved in normal "growth", development, and reproduction.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] Ethylene exemplifies a primary metabolite produced large-scale by industrial microbiology.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] A secondary metabolite is not directly involved in those processes, but usually has an important ecological function.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] Examples include antibiotics and pigments such as resins and terpenes etc.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] Some antibiotics use primary metabolites as precursors, such as actinomycin, which is created from the primary metabolite tryptophan.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] Some sugars are metabolites, such as fructose or glucose, which are both present in the metabolic pathways.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] The metabolome forms a large network of metabolic reactions, where outputs from one enzymatic chemical reaction are inputs to other chemical reactions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] Metabolites from chemical compounds, whether inherent or pharmaceutical, form as part of the natural biochemical process of degrading and eliminating the compounds.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] The rate of degradation of a compound is an important determinant of the duration and intensity of its action.
[src:metabolomics/metabolite] Understanding how pharmaceutical compounds are metabolized and the potential side effects of their metabolites is an important part of drug discovery.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The **metabolome** is the complete set of small-molecule chemicals found within a biological sample.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The biological sample can be a cell, a cellular organelle, an organ, a tissue, a tissue extract, a biofluid or an entire organism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] In other words, there is both an endogenous metabolome and an exogenous metabolome.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The endogenous metabolome can be further subdivided to include a "primary" and a "secondary" metabolome (particularly when referring to plant or microbial metabolomes).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] A primary metabolite is directly involved in the normal growth, development, and reproduction.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] A secondary metabolite is not directly involved in those processes, but usually has important ecological function.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Secondary metabolites may include pigments, antibiotics or waste products derived from partially metabolized xenobiotics.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The study of the metabolome is called metabolomics.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The word metabolome appears to be a blending of the words "metabolite" and "chromosome".
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] It was constructed to imply that metabolites are indirectly encoded by genes or act on genes and gene products.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The term "metabolome" was first used in 1998 and was likely coined to match with existing biological terms referring to the complete set of genes (the genome), the complete set of proteins (the proteome) and the complete set of transcripts (the transcriptome).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The first book on metabolomics was published in 2003.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The first journal dedicated to metabolomics (titled simply "Metabolomics") was launched in 2005 and is currently edited by Prof.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Some of the more significant early papers on metabolome analysis are listed in the references below.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The metabolome reflects the interaction between an organism's genome and its environment.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] As a result, an organism's metabolome can serve as an excellent probe of its phenotype (i.e. the product of its genotype and its environment).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Metabolites can be measured (identified, quantified or classified) using a number of different technologies including NMR spectroscopy and mass spectrometry.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Most mass spectrometry (MS) methods must be coupled to various forms of liquid chromatography (LC), gas chromatography (GC) or capillary electrophoresis (CE) to facilitate compound separation.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Each method is typically able to identify or characterize 50-5,000 different metabolites or metabolite "features" at a time, depending on the instrument or protocol being used.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Currently it is not possible to analyze the entire range of metabolites by a single analytical method.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy is an analytical chemistry technique that measures the absorption of radiofrequency radiation of specific nuclei when molecules containing those nuclei are placed in strong magnetic fields.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The frequency (i.e. the chemical shift) at which a given atom or nucleus absorbs is highly dependent on the chemical environment (bonding, chemical structure nearest neighbours, solvent) of that atom in a given molecule.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The NMR absorption patterns produce "resonance" peaks at different frequencies or different chemical shifts – this collection of peaks is called an NMR spectrum.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Because each chemical compound has a different chemical structure, each compound will have a unique (or almost unique) NMR spectrum.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] As a result, NMR is particularly useful for the characterization, identification and quantification of small molecules, such as metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The widespread use of NMR for "classical" metabolic studies, along with its exceptional capacity to handle complex metabolite mixtures is likely the reason why NMR was one of the first technologies to be widely adopted for routine metabolome measurements.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] As an analytical technique, NMR is non-destructive, non-biased, easily quantifiable, requires little or no separation, permits the identification of novel compounds and it needs no chemical derivatization.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] NMR is particularly amenable to detecting compounds that are less tractable to LC-MS analysis, such as sugars, amines or volatile liquids or GC-MS analysis, such as large molecules (>500 Da) or relatively non-reactive compounds.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] NMR is not a very sensitive technique with a lower limit of detection of about 5 μM.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Typically 50-150 compounds can be identified by NMR-based metabolomic studies.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Mass spectrometry is an analytical technique that measures the mass-to-charge ratio of molecules.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The charged molecules are then propelled through space using electrodes or magnets and their speed, rate of curvature, or other physical characteristics are measured to determine their mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] From these data the mass of the parent molecule can be determined.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Further fragmentation of the molecule through controlled collisions with gas molecules or with electrons can help determine the structure of molecules.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Very accurate mass measurements can also be used to determine the elemental formulas or elemental composition of compounds.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Most forms of mass spectrometry require some form of separation using liquid chromatography or gas chromatography.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] This separation step is required to simplify the resulting mass spectra and to permit more accurate compound identification.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Some mass spectrometry methods also require that the molecules be derivatized or chemically modified so that they are more amenable for chromatographic separation (this is particularly true for GC-MS).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] As an analytical technique, MS is a very sensitive method that requires very little sample (<1 ng of material or <10 μL of a biofluid) and can generate signals for thousands of metabolites from a single sample.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] MS instruments can also be configured for very high throughput metabolome analyses (hundreds to thousands of samples a day).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Quantification of metabolites and the characterization of novel compound structures is more difficult by MS than by NMR.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] LC-MS is particularly amenable to detecting hydrophobic molecules (lipids, fatty acids) and peptides while GC-MS is best for detecting small molecules (<500 Da) and highly volatile compounds (esters, amines, ketones, alkanes, thiols).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Unlike the genome or even the proteome, the metabolome is a highly dynamic entity that can change dramatically, over a period of just seconds or minutes.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] As a result, there is growing interest in measuring metabolites over multiple time periods or over short time intervals using modified versions of NMR or MS-based metabolomics.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Because an organism's metabolome is largely defined by its genome, different species will have different metabolomes.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Indeed, the fact that the metabolome of a tomato is different from the metabolome of an apple is the reason why these two fruits taste so different.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Furthermore, different tissues, different organs and biofluids associated with those organs and tissues can also have distinctly different metabolomes.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The fact that different organisms and different tissues/biofluids have such different metabolomes has led to the development of a number of organism-specific and biofluid-specific metabolome databases.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The latter three databases are specific to human biofluids.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] A number of very popular general metabolite databases also exist including KEGG, MetaboLights, the Golm Metabolome Database, MetaCyc, LipidMaps and Metlin.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The Human Metabolome Database (HMDB) is a freely available, open-access database containing detailed data on more than 40,000 metabolites that have already been identified or are likely to be found in the human body.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The chemical data includes >40,000 metabolite structures with detailed descriptions, extensive chemical classifications, synthesis information and observed/calculated chemical properties.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] It also contains nearly 10,000 experimentally measured NMR, GC-MS and LC/MS spectra from more than 1,100 different metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The clinical information includes data on >10,000 metabolite-biofluid concentrations, metabolite concentration information on more than 600 different human diseases and pathway data for more than 200 different inborn errors of metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The biochemical information includes nearly 6,000 protein (and DNA) sequences and more than 5,000 biochemical reactions that are linked to these metabolite entries.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The HMDB supports a wide variety of online queries including text searches, chemical structure searches, sequence similarity searches and spectral similarity searches.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] This makes it particularly useful for metabolomic researchers who are attempting to identify or understand metabolites in clinical metabolomic studies.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The first version of the HMDB was released in Jan.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] 1 2007 and was compiled by scientists at the University of Alberta and the University of Calgary.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] At that time, they reported data on 2,500 metabolites, 1,200 drugs and 3,500 food components.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Since then these scientists have greatly expanded the collection.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The version 3.5 of the HMDB contains >16,000 endogenous metabolites, >1,500 drugs and >22,000 food constituents or food metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Scientists at the University of Alberta have been systematically characterizing specific biofluid metabolomes including the serum metabolome, the urine metabolome, the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) metabolome and the saliva metabolome.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] These efforts have involved both experimental metabolomic analysis (involving NMR, GC-MS, ICP-MS, LC-MS and HPLC assays) as well as extensive literature mining.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The Yeast Metabolome Database is a freely accessible, online database of >2,000 small molecule metabolites found in or produced by Saccharomyces cerevisiae (Baker's yeast).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The chemical information in YMDB includes 2,027 metabolite structures with detailed metabolite descriptions, extensive chemical classifications, synthesis information and observed/calculated chemical properties.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] It also contains nearly 4,000 NMR, GC-MS and LC/MS spectra obtained from more than 500 different metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The biochemical information in YMDB includes >1,100 protein (and DNA) sequences and >900 biochemical reactions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The YMDB supports a wide variety of queries including text searches, chemical structure searches, sequence similarity searches and spectral similarity searches.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] This makes it particularly useful for metabolomic researchers who are studying yeast as a model organism or who are looking into optimizing the production of fermented beverages (wine, beer).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Secondary electrospray ionization-high resolution mass spectrometry SESI-HRMS is a non-invasive analytical technique that allows us to monitor the yeast metabolic activities.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] SESI-HRMS has found around 300 metabolites in the yeast fermentation process, this suggests that a large number of glucose metabolites are not reported in the literature.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Coli Metabolome Database is a freely accessible, online database of >2,700 small molecule metabolites found in or produced by Escherichia coli (E. coli strain K12, MG1655).
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The chemical information includes more than 2,700 metabolite structures with detailed metabolite descriptions, extensive chemical classifications, synthesis information and observed/calculated chemical properties.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] It also contains nearly 5,000 NMR, GC-MS and LC-MS spectra from more than 600 different metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The biochemical information includes >1,600 protein (and DNA) sequences and >3,100 biochemical reactions that are linked to these metabolite entries.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The ECMDB supports many different types of online queries including text searches, chemical structure searches, sequence similarity searches and spectral similarity searches.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] This makes it particularly useful for metabolomic researchers who are studying E. coli as a model organism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Secondary electrospray ionization (SESI-MS) can discriminate between eleven E.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Coli strains thanks to the volatile organic compound profiling.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] In 2021, the first brain metabolome atlas of the mouse brain – and of an animal (a mammal) across different life stages – was released online.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] The data differentiates by brain regions and the metabolic changes could be "mapped to existing gene and protein brain atlases".
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] Human intestinal microbiota contribute to the etiology of colorectal cancer via their metabolome.
[src:metabolomics/metabolome] In particular, the conversion of primary bile acids to secondary bile acids as a consequence of bacterial metabolism in the colon promotes carcinogenesis.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Messenger RNA (mRNA), gene expression data, and proteomic analyses reveal the set of gene products being produced in the cell, data that represents one aspect of cellular function.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Conversely, metabolic profiling can give an instantaneous snapshot of the physiology of that cell, and thus, metabolomics provides a direct "functional readout of the physiological state" of an organism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] There are indeed quantifiable correlations between the metabolome and the other cellular ensembles (genome, transcriptome, proteome, and lipidome), which can be used to predict metabolite abundances in biological samples from, for example mRNA abundances.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] One of the ultimate challenges of systems biology is to integrate metabolomics with all other -omics information to provide a better understanding of cellular biology.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] However, it was only through technological advancements in the 1960s and 1970s that it became feasible to quantitatively (as opposed to qualitatively) measure metabolic profiles.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The term "metabolic profile" was introduced by Horning, *et al.* in 1971 after they demonstrated that gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS) could be used to measure compounds present in human urine and tissue extracts.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The Horning group, along with that of Linus Pauling and Arthur B.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Robinson led the development of GC-MS methods to monitor the metabolites present in urine through the 1970s.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Concurrently, NMR spectroscopy, which was discovered in the 1940s, was also undergoing rapid advances.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In 1974, Seeley et al. demonstrated the utility of using NMR to detect metabolites in unmodified biological samples.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This first study on muscle highlighted the value of NMR in that it was determined that 90% of cellular ATP is complexed with magnesium.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] As sensitivity has improved with the evolution of higher magnetic field strengths and magic angle spinning, NMR continues to be a leading analytical tool to investigate metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Recent efforts to utilize NMR for metabolomics have been largely driven by the laboratory of Jeremy K.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Nicholson at Birkbeck College, University of London and later at Imperial College London.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In 1984, Nicholson showed 1H NMR spectroscopy could potentially be used to diagnose diabetes mellitus, and later pioneered the application of pattern recognition methods to NMR spectroscopic data.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In 1994 and 1996, liquid chromatography mass spectrometry metabolomics experiments were performed by Gary Siuzdak while working with Richard Lerner (then president of the Scripps Research Institute) and Benjamin Cravatt, to analyze the cerebral spinal fluid from sleep deprived animals.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] One molecule of particular interest, oleamide, was observed and later shown to have sleep inducing properties.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This work is one of the earliest such experiments combining liquid chromatography and mass spectrometry in metabolomics.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In 2005, the first metabolomics tandem mass spectrometry database, METLIN, for characterizing human metabolites was developed in the Siuzdak laboratory at the Scripps Research Institute.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] METLIN is the largest repository of tandem mass spectrometry data of its kind.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The dedicated academic journal Metabolomics first appeared in 2005, founded by its current editor-in-chief Roy Goodacre.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Called XCMS, it has since (2012) been developed as an online tool and as of 2019 (with METLIN) has over 30,000 registered users.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] On 23 January 2007, the Human Metabolome Project, led by David S.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Wishart, completed the first draft of the human metabolome, consisting of a database of approximately 2,500 metabolites, 1,200 drugs and 3,500 food components.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Similar projects have been underway in several plant species, most notably *Medicago truncatula* and *Arabidopsis thaliana* for several years.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] As late as mid-2010, metabolomics was still considered an "emerging field".
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Further, it was noted that further progress in the field depended in large part, through addressing otherwise "irresolvable technical challenges", by technical evolution of mass spectrometry instrumentation.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In 2015, real-time metabolome profiling was demonstrated for the first time.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The metabolome refers to the complete set of small-molecule (<1.5 kDa) metabolites (such as metabolic intermediates, hormones and other signaling molecules, and secondary metabolites) to be found within a biological sample, such as a single organism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The word was coined in analogy with transcriptomics and proteomics; like the transcriptome and the proteome, the metabolome is dynamic, changing from second to second.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Although the metabolome can be defined readily enough, it is not currently possible to analyse the entire range of metabolites by a single analytical method.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In January 2007, scientists at the University of Alberta and the University of Calgary completed the first draft of the human metabolome.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The Human Metabolome Database (HMDB) is perhaps the most extensive public metabolomic spectral database to date and is a freely available electronic database (www.hmdb.ca) containing detailed information about small molecule metabolites found in the human body.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] It is intended to be used for applications in metabolomics, clinical chemistry, biomarker discovery and general education.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The database contains 220,945 metabolite entries including both water-soluble and lipid soluble metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Additionally, 8,610 protein sequences (enzymes and transporters) are linked to these metabolite entries.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Each MetaboCard entry contains 130 data fields with 2/3 of the information being devoted to chemical/clinical data and the other 1/3 devoted to enzymatic or biochemical data.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This information, available at the Human Metabolome Database and based on analysis of information available in the current scientific literature, is far from complete.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In contrast, much more is known about the metabolomes of other organisms.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] For example, over 50,000 metabolites have been characterized from the plant kingdom, and many thousands of metabolites have been identified and/or characterized from single plants.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Each type of cell and tissue has a unique metabolic 'fingerprint' that can elucidate organ or tissue-specific information.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Bio-specimens used for metabolomics analysis include but not limit to plasma, serum, urine, saliva, feces, muscle, sweat, exhaled breath and gastrointestinal fluid.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The ease of collection facilitates high temporal resolution, and because they are always at dynamic equilibrium with the body, they can describe the host as a whole.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Genome can tell what could happen, transcriptome can tell what appears to be happening, proteome can tell what makes it happen and metabolome can tell what has happened and what is happening.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Metabolites are the substrates, intermediates and products of metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Within the context of metabolomics, a metabolite is usually defined as any molecule less than 1.5 kDa in size.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] However, there are exceptions to this depending on the sample and detection method.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] For example, macromolecules such as lipoproteins and albumin are reliably detected in NMR-based metabolomics studies of blood plasma.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In plant-based metabolomics, it is common to refer to "primary" and "secondary" metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Examples include antibiotics and pigments.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] By contrast, in human-based metabolomics, it is more common to describe metabolites as being either endogenous (produced by the host organism) or exogenous.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Metabolites of foreign substances such as drugs are termed xenometabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The metabolome derives from a large network of metabolic reactions, where outputs from one enzymatic chemical reaction are inputs to other chemical reactions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Such systems have been described as hypercycles.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Metabonomics is defined as "the quantitative measurement of the dynamic multiparametric metabolic response of living systems to pathophysiological stimuli or genetic modification".
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The word origin is from the Greek *μεταβολή* meaning change and *nomos* meaning a rule set or set of laws.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This approach was pioneered by Jeremy Nicholson at Murdoch University and has been used in toxicology, disease diagnosis and a number of other fields.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Historically, the metabonomics approach was one of the first methods to apply the scope of systems biology to studies of metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] There has been some disagreement over the exact differences between 'metabolomics' and 'metabonomics'.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] While there is still no absolute agreement, there is a growing consensus that 'metabolomics' places a greater emphasis on metabolic profiling at a cellular or organ level and is primarily concerned with normal endogenous metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] 'Metabonomics' extends metabolic profiling to include information about perturbations of metabolism caused by environmental factors (including diet and toxins), disease processes, and the involvement of extragenomic influences, such as gut microflora.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This is not a trivial difference; metabolomic studies should, by definition, exclude metabolic contributions from extragenomic sources, because these are external to the system being studied.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] However, in practice, within the field of human disease research there is still a large degree of overlap in the way both terms are used, and they are often in effect synonymous.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Exometabolomics, or "metabolic footprinting", is the study of extracellular metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] It uses many techniques from other subfields of metabolomics, and has applications in biofuel development, bioprocessing, determining drugs' mechanism of action, and studying intercellular interactions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The typical workflow of metabolomics studies is shown in the figure.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] First, samples are collected from tissue, plasma, urine, saliva, cells, etc.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Next, metabolites are extracted often with the addition of internal standards and derivatization.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] During sample analysis, metabolites are quantified (liquid chromatography or gas chromatography coupled with MS and/or NMR spectroscopy).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The raw output data can be used for metabolite feature extraction and further processed before statistical analysis (such as principal component analysis, PCA).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Many bioinformatic tools and software are available to identify associations with disease states and outcomes, determine significant correlations, and characterize metabolic signatures with existing biological knowledge.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Initially, analytes in a metabolomic sample comprise a highly complex mixture.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This complex mixture can be simplified prior to detection by separating some analytes from others.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Separation achieves various goals: analytes which cannot be resolved by the detector may be separated in this step; in MS analysis, ion suppression is reduced; the retention time of the analyte serves as information regarding its identity.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This separation step is not mandatory and is often omitted in NMR and "shotgun" based approaches such as shotgun lipidomics.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Gas chromatography (GC), especially when interfaced with mass spectrometry (GC-MS), is a widely used separation technique for metabolomic analysis.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] GC offers very high chromatographic resolution, and can be used in conjunction with a flame ionization detector (GC/FID) or a mass spectrometer (GC-MS).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The method is especially useful for identification and quantification of small and volatile molecules.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] However, a practical limitation of GC is the requirement of chemical derivatization for many biomolecules as only volatile chemicals can be analysed without derivatization.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In cases where greater resolving power is required, two-dimensional chromatography (GCxGC) can be applied.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] High performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) has emerged as the most common separation technique for metabolomic analysis.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] With the advent of electrospray ionization, HPLC was coupled to MS.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In contrast with GC, HPLC has lower chromatographic resolution, but requires no derivatization for polar molecules, and separates molecules in the liquid phase.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Additionally HPLC has the advantage that a much wider range of analytes can be measured with a higher sensitivity than GC methods.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Capillary electrophoresis (CE) has a higher theoretical separation efficiency than HPLC (although requiring much more time per separation), and is suitable for use with a wider range of metabolite classes than is GC.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] As for all electrophoretic techniques, it is most appropriate for charged analytes.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In direct-infusion mass spectrometry (DI-MS), sample is directly introduced into the spectrometer and separation steps are skipped.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] DI-MS can be employed to perform single cell metabolic analysis of human cells.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Mass spectrometry (MS) is used to identify and quantify metabolites after optional separation by GC, HPLC, or CE.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] GC-MS was the first hyphenated technique to be developed.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Identification leverages the distinct patterns in which analytes fragment.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] These patterns can be thought of as a mass spectral fingerprint.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Libraries exist that allow identification of a metabolite according to this fragmentation pattern .
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] MS is both sensitive and can be very specific.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] There are also a number of techniques which use MS as a stand-alone technology: the sample is infused directly into the mass spectrometer with no prior separation, and the MS provides sufficient selectivity to both separate and to detect metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] For analysis by mass spectrometry, the analytes must be imparted with a charge and transferred to the gas phase.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Electron ionization (EI) is the most common ionization technique applied to GC separations as it is amenable to low pressures.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] EI also produces fragmentation of the analyte, both providing structural information while increasing the complexity of the data and possibly obscuring the molecular ion.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Atmospheric-pressure chemical ionization (APCI) is an atmospheric pressure technique that can be applied to all the above separation techniques.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] APCI is a gas phase ionization method, which provides slightly more aggressive ionization than ESI which is suitable for less polar compounds.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Electrospray ionization (ESI) is the most common ionization technique applied in LC/MS/MS especially with triple quadrupole mass spectrometers where multiple reaction monitoring (MRM) or untargeted MRM can be performed.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This soft ionization is most successful for polar molecules with ionizable functional groups.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Another commonly used soft ionization technique is secondary electrospray ionization (SESI).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In the 2000s, surface-based mass analysis has seen a resurgence, with new MS technologies focused on increasing sensitivity, minimizing background, and reducing sample preparation.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The ability to analyze metabolites directly from biofluids and tissues continues to challenge current MS technology, largely because of the limits imposed by the complexity of these samples, which contain thousands to tens of thousands of metabolites.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Among the technologies being developed to address this challenge is Nanostructure-Initiator MS (NIMS), a desorption/ ionization approach that does not require the application of matrix and thereby facilitates small-molecule (i.e., metabolite) identification.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] MALDI is also used; however, the application of a MALDI matrix can add significant background at < 1000 Da that complicates analysis of the low-mass range (i.e., metabolites).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In addition, the size of the resulting matrix crystals limits the spatial resolution that can be achieved in tissue imaging.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Because of these limitations, several other matrix-free desorption/ionization approaches have been applied to the analysis of biofluids and tissues.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Secondary ion mass spectrometry (SIMS) was one of the first matrix-free desorption/ionization approaches used to analyze metabolites from biological samples.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] SIMS uses a high-energy primary ion beam to desorb and generate secondary ions from a surface.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The primary advantage of SIMS is its high spatial resolution (as small as 50 nm), a powerful characteristic for tissue imaging with MS.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] However, SIMS has yet to be readily applied to the analysis of biofluids and tissues because of its limited sensitivity at >500 Da and analyte fragmentation generated by the high-energy primary ion beam.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Desorption electrospray ionization (DESI) is a matrix-free technique for analyzing biological samples that uses a charged solvent spray to desorb ions from a surface.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Advantages of DESI are that no special surface is required and the analysis is performed at ambient pressure with full access to the sample during acquisition.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] A limitation of DESI is spatial resolution because "focusing" the charged solvent spray is difficult.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] However, a recent development termed laser ablation ESI (LAESI) is a promising approach to circumvent this limitation.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Most recently, ion trap techniques such as orbitrap mass spectrometry are also applied to metabolomics research.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy is the only detection technique which does not rely on separation of the analytes, and the sample can thus be recovered for further analyses.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] All kinds of small molecule metabolites can be measured simultaneously - in this sense, NMR is close to being a universal detector.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The main advantages of NMR are high analytical reproducibility and simplicity of sample preparation.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Practically, however, it is relatively insensitive compared to mass spectrometry-based techniques.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Although NMR and MS are the most widely used modern-day techniques for detection, there are other methods in use.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] These include Fourier-transform ion cyclotron resonance, ion-mobility spectrometry, electrochemical detection (coupled to HPLC), Raman spectroscopy and radiolabel (when combined with thin-layer chromatography).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The data generated in metabolomics usually consist of measurements performed on subjects under various conditions.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] These measurements may be digitized spectra, or a list of metabolite features.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In its simplest form, this generates a matrix with rows corresponding to subjects and columns corresponding with metabolite features (or vice versa).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Several statistical programs are currently available for analysis of both NMR and mass spectrometry data.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] A great number of free software are already available for the analysis of metabolomics data shown in the table.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Some statistical tools listed in the table were designed for NMR data analyses were also useful for MS data.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] For mass spectrometry data, software is available that identifies molecules that vary in subject groups on the basis of mass-over-charge value and sometimes retention time depending on the experimental design.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Once metabolite data matrix is determined, unsupervised data reduction techniques (e.g.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] PCA) can be used to elucidate patterns and connections.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In many studies, including those evaluating drug-toxicity and some disease models, the metabolites of interest are not known *a priori*.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This makes unsupervised methods, those with no prior assumptions of class membership, a popular first choice.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The most common of these methods includes principal component analysis (PCA) which can efficiently reduce the dimensions of a dataset to a few which explain the greatest variation.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] When analyzed in the lower-dimensional PCA space, clustering of samples with similar metabolic fingerprints can be detected.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] PCA algorithms aim to replace all correlated variables with a much smaller number of uncorrelated variables (referred to as principal components (PCs)) and retain most of the information in the original dataset.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This clustering can elucidate patterns and assist in the determination of disease biomarkers – metabolites that correlate most with class membership.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Linear models are commonly used for metabolomics data, but are affected by multicollinearity.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] On the other hand, multivariate statistics are thriving methods for high-dimensional correlated metabolomics data, of which the most popular one is Projection to Latent Structures (PLS) regression and its classification version PLS-DA.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Other data mining methods, such as random forest, support-vector machines, etc. are received increasing attention for untargeted metabolomics data analysis.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In the case of univariate methods, variables are analyzed one by one using classical statistics tools (such as Student's t-test, ANOVA or mixed models) and only these with sufficient small p-values are considered relevant.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] However, correction strategies should be used to reduce false discoveries when multiple comparisons are conducted since there is no standard method for measuring the total amount of metabolites directly in untargeted metabolomics.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] For multivariate analysis, models should always be validated to ensure that the results can be generalized.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Machine learning is a powerful tool that can be used in metabolomics analysis.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Recently, scientists have developed retention time prediction software.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] These tools allow researchers to apply artificial intelligence to the retention time prediction of small molecules in complex mixture, such as human plasma, plant extracts, foods, or microbial cultures.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Retention time prediction increases the identification rate in liquid chromatography and can lead to an improved biological interpretation of metabolomics data.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Toxicity assessment/toxicology by metabolic profiling (especially of urine or blood plasma samples) detects the physiological changes caused by toxic insult of a chemical (or mixture of chemicals).
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In many cases, the observed changes can be related to specific syndromes, e.g. a specific lesion in liver or kidney.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This is of particular relevance to pharmaceutical companies wanting to test the toxicity of potential drug candidates: if a compound can be eliminated before it reaches clinical trials on the grounds of adverse toxicity, it saves the enormous expense of the trials.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] For functional genomics, metabolomics can be an excellent tool for determining the phenotype caused by a genetic manipulation, such as gene deletion or insertion.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Sometimes this can be a sufficient goal in itself—for instance, to detect any phenotypic changes in a genetically modified plant intended for human or animal consumption.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] More exciting is the prospect of predicting the function of unknown genes by comparison with the metabolic perturbations caused by deletion/insertion of known genes.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Such advances are most likely to come from model organisms such as *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* and *Arabidopsis thaliana*.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Metabologenomics is a novel approach to integrate metabolomics and genomics data by correlating microbial-exported metabolites with predicted biosynthetic genes.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] This bioinformatics-based pairing method enables natural product discovery at a larger-scale by refining non-targeted metabolomic analyses to identify small molecules with related biosynthesis and to focus on those that may not have previously well known structures.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Fluxomics is a further development of metabolomics.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The disadvantage of metabolomics is that it only provides the user with abundances or concentrations of metabolites, while fluxomics determines the reaction rates of metabolic reactions and can trace metabolites in a biological system over time.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Nutrigenomics is a generalised term which links genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics and metabolomics to human nutrition.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] In general, in a given body fluid, a metabolome is influenced by endogenous factors such as age, sex, body composition and genetics as well as underlying pathologies.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The large bowel microflora are also a very significant potential confounder of metabolic profiles and could be classified as either an endogenous or exogenous factor.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] The main exogenous factors are diet and drugs.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Diet can then be broken down to nutrients and non-nutrients.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Metabolomics is one means to determine a biological endpoint, or metabolic fingerprint, which reflects the balance of all these forces on an individual's metabolism.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Thanks to recent cost reductions, metabolomics has now become accessible for companion animals, such as pregnant dogs.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Volatolomics is a development of metabolomics that studies volatile organic compounds (VOCs) emitted by a biological systems.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Plant metabolomics is designed to study the overall changes in metabolites of plant samples and then conduct deep data mining and chemometric analysis.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Specialized metabolites are considered components of plant defense systems biosynthesized in response to biotic and abiotic stresses.
[src:metabolomics/metabolomics] Metabolomics approaches have recently been used to assess the natural variance in metabolite content between individual plants, an approach with great potential for the improvement of the compositional quality of crops.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The perturbation of this alignment of the nuclear spins by a weak oscillating magnetic field, usually referred to as a radio-frequency (RF) pulse.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Detection and analysis of the electromagnetic waves emitted by the nuclei of the sample as a result of this perturbation.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Similarly, biochemists use NMR to identify proteins and other complex molecules.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Besides identification, NMR spectroscopy provides detailed information about the structure, dynamics, reaction state, and chemical environment of molecules.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most common types of NMR are proton and carbon-13 NMR spectroscopy, but it is applicable to any kind of sample that contains nuclei possessing spin.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectra are unique, well-resolved, analytically tractable and often highly predictable for small molecules.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Different functional groups are obviously distinguishable, and identical functional groups with differing neighboring substituents still give distinguishable signals.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR has largely replaced traditional wet chemistry tests such as color reagents or typical chromatography for identification.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most significant drawback of NMR spectroscopy is its poor sensitivity (compared to other analytical methods, such as mass spectrometry).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Typically 2–50 mg of a substance is required to record a decent-quality NMR spectrum.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The NMR method is non-destructive, thus the substance may be recovered.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] To obtain high-resolution NMR spectra, solid substances are usually dissolved to make liquid solutions, although solid-state NMR spectroscopy is also possible.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The timescale of NMR is relatively long, and thus it is not suitable for observing fast phenomena, producing only an averaged spectrum.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Although large amounts of impurities do show on an NMR spectrum, better methods exist for detecting impurities, as NMR is inherently not very sensitive – though at higher frequencies, sensitivity is higher.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Correlation spectroscopy is a development of ordinary NMR.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In two-dimensional NMR, the emission is centered around a single frequency, and correlated resonances are observed.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This allows identifying the neighboring substituents of the observed functional group, allowing unambiguous identification of the resonances.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There are also more complex 3D and 4D methods and a variety of methods designed to suppress or amplify particular types of resonances.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) spectroscopy, the relaxation of the resonances is observed.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] As NOE depends on the proximity of the nuclei, quantifying the NOE for each nucleus allows construction of a three-dimensional model of the molecule.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectrometers are relatively expensive; universities usually have them, but they are less common in private companies.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Between 2000 and 2015, an NMR spectrometer cost around 0.5–5 million USD.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Modern NMR spectrometers have a very strong, large and expensive liquid-helium-cooled superconducting magnet, because resolution directly depends on magnetic field strength.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Higher magnetic field also improves the sensitivity of the NMR spectroscopy, which depends on the population difference between the two nuclear levels, which increases exponentially with the magnetic field strength.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Less expensive machines using permanent magnets and lower resolution are also available, which still give sufficient performance for certain applications such as reaction monitoring and quick checking of samples.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There are even benchtop nuclear magnetic resonance spectrometers.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectra of protons (1H nuclei) can be observed even in Earth magnetic field.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Low-resolution NMR produces broader peaks, which can easily overlap one another, causing issues in resolving complex structures.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The use of higher-strength magnetic fields result in a better sensitivity and higher resolution of the peaks, and it is preferred for research purposes.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Credit for the discovery of NMR goes to Isidor Isaac Rabi, who received the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1944.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The Purcell group at Harvard University and the Bloch group at Stanford University independently developed NMR spectroscopy in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Edward Mills Purcell and Felix Bloch shared the 1952 Nobel Prize in Physics for their inventions.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The key determinant of NMR activity in atomic nuclei is the nuclear spin quantum number (*I*).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This intrinsic quantum property, similar to an atom's "spin", characterizes the angular momentum of the nucleus.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] To be NMR-active, a nucleus must have a non-zero nuclear spin (*I* ≠ 0).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is this non-zero spin that enables nuclei to interact with external magnetic fields and show signals in NMR.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Atoms with an odd sum of protons and neutrons exhibit half-integer values for the nuclear spin quantum number (*I* = 1/2, 3/2, 5/2, and so on).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These atoms are NMR-active because they possess non-zero nuclear spin.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Atoms with an even sum but both an odd number of protons and an odd number of neutrons exhibit integer nuclear spins (*I* = 1, 2, 3, and so on).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Conversely, atoms with an even number of both protons and neutrons have a nuclear spin quantum number of zero (*I* = 0), and therefore are not NMR-active.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR-active nuclei, particularly those with a spin quantum number of 1/2, are of great significance in NMR spectroscopy.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] When placed in a magnetic field, NMR active nuclei (such as 1H or 13C) absorb electromagnetic radiation at a frequency characteristic of the isotope.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The resonant frequency, energy of the radiation absorbed, and the intensity of the signal are proportional to the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, in a 21-tesla magnetic field, hydrogen nuclei (protons) resonate at 900 MHz.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is common to refer to a 21 T magnet as a 900 MHz magnet, since hydrogen is the most common nucleus detected.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, different nuclei will resonate at different frequencies at this field strength in proportion to their nuclear magnetic moments.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Spinning the sample is usually necessary to average out diffusional motion, however, some experiments call for a stationary sample when solution movement is an important variable.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For instance, measurements of diffusion constants (*diffusion ordered spectroscopy* or DOSY) are done using a stationary sample with spinning off, and flow cells can be used for online analysis of process flows.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The vast majority of molecules in a solution are solvent molecules, and most regular solvents are hydrocarbons and so contain NMR-active hydrogen-1 nuclei.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In order to avoid having the signals from solvent hydrogen atoms overwhelm the experiment and interfere in analysis of the dissolved analyte, deuterated solvents are used where >99% of the protons are replaced with deuterium (hydrogen-2).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most widely used deuterated solvent is deuterochloroform (CDCl3), although other solvents may be used for various reasons, such as solubility of a sample, desire to control hydrogen bonding, or melting or boiling points.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The chemical shifts of a molecule change slightly between solvents, and therefore the solvent used is almost always reported with chemical shifts.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Proton NMR spectra are often calibrated against the known solvent residual proton peak as an internal standard instead of adding tetramethylsilane (TMS), which is conventionally defined as having a chemical shift of zero.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] To detect the very small frequency shifts due to nuclear magnetic resonance, the applied magnetic field must be extremely uniform throughout the sample volume.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] High-resolution NMR spectrometers use shims to adjust the homogeneity of the magnetic field to parts per billion (ppb) in a volume of a few cubic centimeters.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In modern NMR spectrometers shimming is adjusted automatically, though in some cases the operator has to optimize the shim parameters manually to obtain the best possible resolution.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Upon excitation of the sample with a radio frequency (60–1000 MHz) pulse, a nuclear magnetic resonance response – a free induction decay (FID) – is obtained.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is a very weak signal and requires sensitive radio receivers to pick up.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A Fourier transform is carried out to extract the frequency-domain spectrum from the raw time-domain FID.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A spectrum from a single FID has a low signal-to-noise ratio, but it improves readily with averaging of repeated acquisitions.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Good 1H NMR spectra can be acquired with 16 repeats, which takes only minutes.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, for elements heavier than hydrogen, the relaxation time is rather long, e.g. around 8 seconds for 13C.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Thus, acquisition of quantitative heavy-element spectra can be time-consuming, taking tens of minutes to hours.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Following the pulse, the nuclei are, on average, excited to a certain angle vs. the spectrometer magnetic field.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The extent of excitation can be controlled with the pulse width, typically about 3–8 μs for the optimal 90° pulse.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The pulse width can be determined by plotting the (signed) intensity as a function of pulse width.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It follows a sine curve and, accordingly, changes sign at pulse widths corresponding to 180° and 360° pulses.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Decay times of the excitation, typically measured in seconds, depend on the effectiveness of relaxation, which is faster for lighter nuclei and in solids, slower for heavier nuclei and in solutions, and can be very long in gases.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] If the second excitation pulse is sent prematurely before the relaxation is complete, the average magnetization vector has not decayed to ground state, which affects the strength of the signal in an unpredictable manner.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In practice, the peak areas are then not proportional to the stoichiometry; only the presence, but not the amount of functional groups is possible to discern.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] An inversion recovery experiment can be done to determine the relaxation time and thus the required delay between pulses.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A 180° pulse, an adjustable delay, and a 90° pulse is transmitted.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] When the 90° pulse exactly cancels out the signal, the delay corresponds to the time needed for 90° of relaxation.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Inversion recovery is worthwhile for quantitative 13C, 2D and other time-consuming experiments.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR signals are ordinarily characterized by three variables: chemical shift, spin–spin coupling, and relaxation time.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The energy difference Δ*E* between nuclear spin states is proportional to the magnetic field (Zeeman effect). Δ*E* is also sensitive to the electronic environment of the nucleus, giving rise to what is known as the chemical shift, δ.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The simplest types of NMR graphs are plots of the different chemical shifts of the nuclei being studied in the molecule.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The value of δ is often expressed in terms of "shielding": shielded nuclei have higher Δ*E*.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The range of δ values is called the dispersion.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is rather small for 1H signals, but much larger for other nuclei.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR signals are reported relative to a reference signal, usually that of TMS (tetramethylsilane).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Additionally, since the distribution of NMR signals is field-dependent, these frequencies are divided by the spectrometer frequency.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, since we are dividing Hz by MHz, the resulting number would be too small, and thus it is multiplied by a million.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This operation therefore gives a locator number called the "chemical shift" with units of parts per million.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The chemical shift provides structural information.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The conversion of chemical shifts (and J's, see below) is called *assigning* the spectrum.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For diamagnetic organic compounds, assignments of 1H and 13C NMR spectra are extremely sophisticated because of the large databases and easy computational tools.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In general, chemical shifts for protons are highly predictable, since the shifts are primarily determined by shielding effects (electron density).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The chemical shifts for many heavier nuclei are more strongly influenced by other factors, including excited states ("paramagnetic" contribution to shielding tensor).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This paramagnetic contribution, which is unrelated to paramagnetism, not only disrupts trends in chemical shifts, which complicates assignments, but it also gives rise to very large chemical shift ranges.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, most 1H NMR signals for most organic compounds are within 15 ppm.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For 31P NMR, the range is hundreds of ppm.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In paramagnetic NMR spectroscopy, the samples are paramagnetic, i.e. they contain unpaired electrons.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The paramagnetism gives rise to very diverse chemical shifts.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In 1H NMR spectroscopy, the chemical shift range can span up to thousands of ppm.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Some of the most useful information for structure determination in a one-dimensional NMR spectrum comes from J-coupling, or scalar coupling (a special case of spin–spin coupling), between NMR active nuclei.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This coupling arises from the interaction of different spin states through the chemical bonds of a molecule and results in the splitting of NMR signals.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For a proton, the local magnetic field is slightly different depending on whether an adjacent nucleus points towards or against the spectrometer magnetic field, which gives rise to two signals per proton instead of one.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These splitting patterns can be complex or simple and, likewise, can be straightforwardly interpretable or deceptive.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This coupling provides detailed insight into the connectivity of atoms in a molecule.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The multiplicity of the splitting is an effect of the spins of the nuclei that are coupled and the number of such nuclei involved in the coupling.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling to *n* equivalent spin-1/2 nuclei splits the signal into a *n* + 1 multiplet with intensity ratios following Pascal's triangle as described in the table.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling to additional spins leads to further splittings of each component of the multiplet, e.g. coupling to two different spin-1/2 nuclei with significantly different coupling constants leads to a *doublet of doublets* (abbreviation: dd).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] *Long-range* couplings over more than three bonds can often be observed in cyclic and aromatic compounds, leading to more complex splitting patterns.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, in the proton spectrum for ethanol, the CH3 group is split into a *triplet* with an intensity ratio of 1:2:1 by the two neighboring CH2 protons.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Similarly, the CH2 is split into a *quartet* with an intensity ratio of 1:3:3:1 by the three neighboring CH3 protons.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In principle, the two CH2 protons would also be split again into a *doublet* to form a *doublet of quartets* by the hydroxyl proton, but intermolecular exchange of the acidic hydroxyl proton often results in a loss of coupling information.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling to any spin-1/2 nuclei such as phosphorus-31 or fluorine-19 works in this fashion (although the magnitudes of the coupling constants may be very different).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] But the splitting patterns differ from those described above for nuclei with spin greater than 1/2 because the spin quantum number has more than two possible values.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For instance, coupling to deuterium (a spin-1 nucleus) splits the signal into a *1:1:1 triplet* because the spin 1 has three spin states.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Similarly, a spin-3/2 nucleus such as 35Cl splits a signal into a *1:1:1:1 quartet* and so on.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling combined with the chemical shift (and the integration for protons) tells us not only about the chemical environment of the nuclei, but also the number of *neighboring* NMR active nuclei within the molecule.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In more complex spectra with multiple peaks at similar chemical shifts or in spectra of nuclei other than hydrogen, coupling is often the only way to distinguish different nuclei.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The magnitude of the coupling (the coupling constant *J*) is an effect of how strongly the nuclei are coupled to each other.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For simple cases, this is an effect of the bonding distance between the nuclei, the magnetic moment of the nuclei, and the dihedral angle between them.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The above description assumes that the coupling constant is small in comparison with the difference in NMR frequencies between the inequivalent spins.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] If the shift separation decreases (or the coupling strength increases), the multiplet intensity patterns are first distorted, and then become more complex and less easily analyzed (especially if more than two spins are involved).
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Intensification of some peaks in a multiplet is achieved at the expense of the remainder, which sometimes almost disappear in the background noise, although the integrated area under the peaks remains constant.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In most high-field NMR, however, the distortions are usually modest, and the characteristic distortions (*roofing*) can in fact help to identify related peaks.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Some of these patterns can be analyzed with the method published by John Pople, though it has limited scope.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Second-order effects decrease as the frequency difference between multiplets increases, so that high-field (i.e. high-frequency) NMR spectra display less distortion than lower-frequency spectra.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Early spectra at 60 MHz were more prone to distortion than spectra from later machines typically operating at frequencies at 200 MHz or above.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Furthermore, as in the figure to the right, J-coupling can be used to identify ortho-meta-para substitution of a ring.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Ortho coupling is the strongest at 15 Hz, Meta follows with an average of 2 Hz, and finally para coupling is usually insignificant for studies.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] More subtle effects can occur if chemically equivalent spins (i.e., nuclei related by symmetry and so having the same NMR frequency) have different coupling relationships to external spins.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Spins that are chemically equivalent but are not indistinguishable (based on their coupling relationships) are termed magnetically inequivalent.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, the 4 H sites of 1,2-dichlorobenzene divide into two chemically equivalent pairs by symmetry, but an individual member of one of the pairs has different couplings to the spins making up the other pair.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Magnetic inequivalence can lead to highly complex spectra, which can only be analyzed by computational modeling.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Such effects are more common in NMR spectra of aromatic and other non-flexible systems, while conformational averaging about C−C bonds in flexible molecules tends to equalize the couplings between protons on adjacent carbons, reducing problems with magnetic inequivalence.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Correlation spectroscopy is one of several types of two-dimensional nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy or 2D-NMR.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This type of NMR experiment is best known by its acronym, COSY.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Other types of two-dimensional NMR include J-spectroscopy, exchange spectroscopy (EXSY), Nuclear Overhauser effect spectroscopy (NOESY), total correlation spectroscopy (TOCSY), and heteronuclear correlation experiments, such as HSQC, HMQC, and HMBC.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In correlation spectroscopy, emission is centered on the peak of an individual nucleus; if its magnetic field is correlated with another nucleus by through-bond (COSY, HSQC, etc.) or through-space (NOE) coupling, a response can also be detected on the frequency of the correlated nucleus.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Two-dimensional NMR spectra provide more information about a molecule than one-dimensional NMR spectra and are especially useful in determining the structure of a molecule, particularly for molecules that are too complicated to work with using one-dimensional NMR.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The first two-dimensional experiment, COSY, was proposed by Jean Jeener, a professor at Université Libre de Bruxelles, in 1971.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This experiment was later implemented by Walter P.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Ernst, who published their work in 1976.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A variety of physical circumstances do not allow molecules to be studied in solution, and at the same time not by other spectroscopic techniques to an atomic level, either.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In solid-phase media, such as crystals, microcrystalline powders, gels, anisotropic solutions, etc., it is in particular the dipolar coupling and chemical shift anisotropy that become dominant to the behaviour of the nuclear spin systems.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In conventional solution-state NMR spectroscopy, these additional interactions would lead to a significant broadening of spectral lines.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A variety of techniques allows establishing high-resolution conditions, that can, at least for 13C spectra, be comparable to solution-state NMR spectra.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Two important concepts for high-resolution solid-state NMR spectroscopy are the limitation of possible molecular orientation by sample orientation, and the reduction of anisotropic nuclear magnetic interactions by sample spinning.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Of the latter approach, fast spinning around the magic angle is a very prominent method, when the system comprises spin-1/2 nuclei.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Spinning rates of about 20 kHz are used, which demands special equipment.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A number of intermediate techniques, with samples of partial alignment or reduced mobility, is currently being used in NMR spectroscopy.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Applications in which solid-state NMR effects occur are often related to structure investigations on membrane proteins, protein fibrils or all kinds of polymers, and chemical analysis in inorganic chemistry, but also include "exotic" applications like the plant leaves and fuel cells.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, Rahmani et al. studied the effect of pressure and temperature on the bicellar structures' self-assembly using deuterium NMR spectroscopy.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Solid-state NMR is useful also for metal structure understanding in case of X-ray amorphous metal samples (like nano-size refractory metal 99Tc) .
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Recent studies have combined solid-state NMR with molecular dynamics simulations to resolve nanosecond-to-millisecond-scale motions in hydrated materials like amorphous calcium carbonate.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Much of the innovation within NMR spectroscopy has been within the field of protein NMR spectroscopy, an important technique in structural biology.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A common goal of these investigations is to obtain high resolution 3-dimensional structures of the protein, similar to what can be achieved by X-ray crystallography.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In contrast to X-ray crystallography, NMR spectroscopy is usually limited to proteins smaller than 35 kDa, although larger structures have been solved.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectroscopy is often the only way to obtain high resolution information on partially or wholly intrinsically unstructured proteins.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is now a common tool for the determination of Conformation Activity Relationships where the structure before and after interaction with, for example, a drug candidate is compared to its known biochemical activity.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Proteins are orders of magnitude larger than the small organic molecules discussed earlier in this article, but the basic NMR techniques and some NMR theory also applies.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Because of the much higher number of atoms present in a protein molecule in comparison with a small organic compound, the basic 1D spectra become crowded with overlapping signals to an extent where direct spectral analysis becomes untenable.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Therefore, multidimensional (2, 3 or 4D) experiments have been devised to deal with this problem.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most important method used for structure determination of proteins utilizes NOE experiments to measure distances between atoms within the molecule.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Subsequently, the distances obtained are used to generate a 3D structure of the molecule by solving a distance geometry problem.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR can also be used to obtain information on the dynamics and conformational flexibility of different regions of a protein.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Nucleic acid NMR is the use of NMR spectroscopy to obtain information about the structure and dynamics of polynucleic acids, such as DNA or RNA.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] As of 2003, nearly half of all known RNA structures had been determined by NMR spectroscopy.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Nucleic acid and protein NMR spectroscopy are similar but differences exist.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Nucleic acids have a smaller percentage of hydrogen atoms, which are the atoms usually observed in NMR spectroscopy, and because nucleic acid double helices are stiff and roughly linear, they do not fold back on themselves to give "long-range" correlations.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The types of NMR usually done with nucleic acids are 1H or proton NMR, 13C NMR, 15N NMR, and 31P NMR.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Parameters taken from the spectrum, mainly NOESY cross-peaks and coupling constants, can be used to determine local structural features such as glycosidic bond angles, dihedral angles (using the Karplus equation), and sugar pucker conformations.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For large-scale structure, these local parameters must be supplemented with other structural assumptions or models, because errors add up as the double helix is traversed, and unlike with proteins, the double helix does not have a compact interior and does not fold back upon itself.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR is also useful for investigating nonstandard geometries such as bent helices, non-Watson–Crick basepairing, and coaxial stacking.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It has been especially useful in probing the structure of natural RNA oligonucleotides, which tend to adopt complex conformations such as stem-loops and pseudoknots.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR is also useful for probing the binding of nucleic acid molecules to other molecules, such as proteins or drugs, by seeing which resonances are shifted upon binding of the other molecule.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Carbohydrate NMR spectroscopy addresses questions on the structure and conformation of carbohydrates.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The analysis of carbohydrates by 1H NMR is challenging due to the limited variation in functional groups, which leads to 1H resonances concentrated in narrow bands of the NMR spectrum.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In other words, there is poor spectral dispersion.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The anomeric proton resonances are segregated from the others due to fact that the anomeric carbons bear two oxygen atoms.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For smaller carbohydrates, the dispersion of the anomeric proton resonances facilitates the use of 1D TOCSY experiments to investigate the entire spin systems of individual carbohydrate residues.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Knowledge of energy minima and rotational energy barriers of small molecules in solution can be found using NMR, e.g. looking at free ligand conformational preferences and conformational dynamics, respectively.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This can be used to guide drug design hypotheses, since experimental and calculated values are comparable.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, AstraZeneca uses NMR for its oncology research & development.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] One of the first scientific works devoted to the use of pressure as a variable parameter in NMR experiments was the work of J.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Jonas published in the journal Annual Review of Biophysics in 1994.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The use of high pressures in NMR spectroscopy was primarily driven by the desire to study biochemical systems, where the use of high pressure allows controlled changes in intermolecular interactions without significant perturbations.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Of course, attempts have been made to solve scientific problems using high-pressure NMR spectroscopy.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, most of them were difficult to reproduce due to the problem of equipment for creating and maintaining high pressure.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In the most common types of NMR cells for realization of high-pressure NMR experiments are given.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] High-pressure NMR spectroscopy has been widely used for a variety of applications, mainly related to the characterization of the structure of protein molecules.
[src:metabolomics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, in recent years, software and design solutions have been proposed to characterize the chemical and spatial structures of small molecules in a supercritical fluid environment, using state parameters as a driving force for such changes.
